			<div class="content" id="post-content-3870148">
									

<blockquote>
<p>although the term was not used in the Wehrmacht as far as I know.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Huh? There's the one super famous <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Afrika_korps" onclick="window.open(this.href, '_blank'); return false;">German expeditionsry corps</a>. But there were hundreds of corps level organizations, here's <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_German_corps_in_World_War_II" onclick="window.open(this.href, '_blank'); return false;">a list</a>.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Not to mention that the term does not sound like anything the SS would come up with</p>
</blockquote>
<p>The SS also had corps (see the same list). As far as &quot;obskura&quot; goes, I don't think that it is that out of line with other occult sounding words in (mis-) use within the <em>Ahnenerbe</em> (and Nazi mysticism in general, e.g. &quot;santur&quot;).</p>
<p>The main conceit here is that an Ahnenerbe element was organized as a corps, which yes is total historical nonsense, but so is the whole secret wizard war to begin with.</p>

