					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dr-grom" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2026083); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2026083&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610182118" alt="Dr_Grom" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2026083)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dr-grom" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2026083); return false;" >Dr_Grom</a></span> <span class="odate time_1531377261 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">12 Jul 2018 06:34</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3870868">
									

<p>Well I think the Totenkopf of the SS originated from the skulls that some elite soldiers from the WWI storm battalions and some pioneers wore. I think it is rather a symbol of elitism and self-sacrifice than of villainy. According to the official description of the Totenkopfringe it stands for &quot;the reminder to at all times be ready to give the life of our self for the life of the entirety&quot;.<br />
It was also already used before WWI, by units that thereby told their foe they would not take prisoners, nor be taken. Also British and US forces have used skulls in their heraldy and traditions too, and some US forces are still using it. I don't think it is to be considered a symbol of villainy here either.<br />
The term &quot;Blutfahne&quot; origins from the Holy Roman Empire and symbolized the Emperors high justice. &quot;Sonnenrad&quot; is nothing extraordinary, just another symbol.<br />
I think all these and other symbols as well as the black SS uniforms, use of runes etc. were meant to create a mysticism to attract recruits and strengthen the bond of the units. The principle is normal in military, in the past and present. All military units have their symbols, their rituals, traditions and such. The Nazis knew very well how to use these to control the masses. You can see similar heavy use of symbols in many communist states and fascist dictatorships as well as the Roman Empire.</p>

